review_blob: I cant figure out why people would want to order this in a bar anywhere but Australia.  Why pay the import price for another macro?  Just give me the extra couple of bucks, Ill get you a tall PBR and well call it a day.  Nothing different here except that it might stink a little more than most domestic macros.

How can they advertise this as an ale.  Hard to differentiate this from the regular.  I suppose it is a bit bitter on the finish, but I found the difference to be pretty negligible.  Dont waste your time.

Pale golden color with soft fluffy head.  Scent is malty as is the taste.  Too much in both departments for me.  I was expecting more because of the brewer, but this my least favorite of any Ayinger Ive had.

This isnt one of my favorite styles, but this version is pretty good.  Dark copper/ruby color, minimal head.  High malt presence, pretty light on the hops.  However, there is enough hops here to tone down the sweetness of the malt.  Really nice balnce here.
Pretty dark for a wheat beer.  Traces of apple and clove.  Quite carbonated.  The nice head seemed to dissapear pretty quickly.  I would prefer a little more hops, but its still awful good.

Pours a dark hazy orange.  Smallish, but lasting head.  Faint hint of citrus, maybe grapefruit/lemon.  Has a nice hops kick, but nothing that overpowers the other subtle flavors.  Somewhat toward the mild end, but very good nonetheless.

Golden amber color.  I enjoyed this more than the Reverend.  Not as overtly sweet.  I tended to taste a spicy peach sensation rather than the citrus others have mentioned.  The high alcohol seemed masked pretty well to me.  Enjoyed this one.

Better than the nitrogen infused draught botttles and cans.  If you have to drink Guinness prepackaged this is the way to go.Earlier Rating: 10/27/2004 Total Score: 3.3Dark color with the tan head.  I love pale ale, and I love Guinness draught, so I thought this would be perfect.  Perhaps my expectations were too high.  Has the roasty choco-coffee flavor with a bitter finish.  Would probably really enjoy this had I never had the original.

For a long time, this was my beer of choice.  Its still a great standby, but Im really into hoppy pale ales right now.  Great coffee cocoa taste.  Still has to be about the best looking pint out there.  Rich and creamy in your mouth.  Only bother with the cans if there is no other alternative.

This along with Guinness used to be two of my faves.   Ive since gotten into the hoppier set.  Still doesnt dissapoint.  The roasted chocolate tones stand out.  I dont think this feels as thick and creamy as Guinness.  They both taste much better on tap.
Tried this stuff in school and struggled mightily to get through the bottle.  Im not even sure they still make this stuff, but let me assure you, it is shit to the nth degree.
This stuffs bad.  And unlike another reviewer here, Id take Hamms or Beast over this any day of the week.
Not as bad as I was expecting (everything that is Colt 45 X 2)  Kinda sweet.  Luckily you dont need a bunch of these to get that buzz going.
Wow Billy Dee, how could you endorse this crap.  It is better than King Cobra, but let me tell you, thats not saying much.
It was on the list so I had to try it.  Id have to say malt liquor is malt liquor.  Itll get you dinged up, but you probably wont enjoy what youve got to taste to get there.

Not too bad for this type.  Doesnt do anything to offend.  Clear yellow color.  I was lucky enough to get some of this that wasnt skunked.  Somewhat of a grassy taste.  The bottles are pretty nifty though.
Decent amber.  You get a hint of the hops (though not enough for me)  Doesnt have anything that would make it stand out from many other beeers of this type.
Creamy dark color.  The taste is hat youd expect.  Coffee flavor is dominant throughout.  Pretty good.
Cloudy light amber color.  The hint of fruit and spice is a very pleasant aroma.  The slightly bitter finish is a nice compliment to the hint of fruit tasted earlier.
Dark amber color.  Tastes like the lager with a hint of spice.  Wouldnt go out of my way for it.
Very light golden hue.  Not much head to speak of.  The aroma is a faint combonation of floral/citrus.  Decent as far as pilseners go.
Copper color minimal head.  Very faint taste of chocolate.  Liked that the hops was noticeable.
Deep gold in color with a slight cloudiness.  Lightly spicy and a faint hint of citrus.  All in all pretty good.
Pretty decent as far as light beers go.  I just dont see the point.  Eat a healthy diet, and allow yourself to drink good beer.
Like the light amber cloudy look.  Smells very pleasant as well.  Feels nice and creamy in the mouth, but the cherry flavor is a little too emphatic.
This beer just never did it for me.  Maybe because Im not a big lager fan.  Too bad their ale didnt get the sales push that this did.

Color is a medium brown with a touch of red.  Faint caramel malty scent.  Mild hops flavor.  No one thing seems to stand out, but the package is very good.  My favorite in the Sam Adams stable.  Wish it was as easily accesible here as the lager.
One and done here.  No flavor or scent to speak of.  A little darker than water.  Ill stick to something with some taste and walk home to burn off the extra carbs and calories I consume.
Not as carbonated or clear as soda water, but does have about the same taste.
Just a light clear yellow color with minimal head.  My favorite of the diet beers, but you wont be seeing me drink too many Cokes either.  More taste than say Aspen Edge or Mich Ultra, but not much.
Nothing real exciting here.  A little more color and flavor than domestic macros.  Nothing stands out that should offend too many taste buds.  Just not alot going on here.

Dark amber/orange color.  Scent is of pumpkin pie.  I really liked this one.  The flavor is a perfect balance.  The pumpkin is prominent, but not overpowering.  Hope to drink some more of this before the seasons out.
beer_name: Blue Moon Harvest Moon Pumpkin Ale

review_blob: Nice cloudy yellow appearance.  Faint citrus scent and taste.  This is really good and refreshing with an orange slice.

Im guessing this should only be drank for the purpose of getting drunk.  Watered down version of Old Mil.  Could probably collect large amounts of empties around trailer parks.  I dont even remember people drinking this one in college.  Thats saying something.

Has a little more flavor than most domestics, but thats not to say its a good flavor.  I think I remember seeing that this one some beer tasting deal not a real long time ago.  Im guessing some of the judges were still left over from giving Pabst their blue ribbon.
Ah, Beast Light.  My favorite cheap watered down keg filler from a  5 year period of heavy drinking and an occasional midterm!

I have no idea why, but this is my favorite domestic macro.  Seems to always be what I oreder when faced with an Anheuser, Miller, Coors only selection.  While the taste isnt that great.  It does at least taste of something.
Always a good binge drinking beer of choice for the college set.  Now that I have a job, I dont find myself buying it much!
Taste (or lack thereof) is just like all the other light macros.  This ones not even good to get sloshed on...gives me ridiculous headaches!
Nothing complex here.  Bud light with a hint of flavor.  Ill get it only when faced with a choice b/t it or Bud Light.
In my opinion the worst of the Anheuser beers.  I cannot fathom how they sell so much of this crap.  Chick beer only.

The high overall rating is for sentimental reasons only.  I consumed gallons upon gallons of this stuff in college.  For 7-8 bucks a case and about 35 a keg, what can you really hope for in terms of flavor?
See Corona review.  Everythings the same except that it is more watered down and has even less taste of beer.  I felt this only made the skunkiness stand out even more.

Dont really see how so many find this one appealing.  Light and watered down.  The only discernable flavor is that of being skunked.  The lime is a neccesity to mask this.  That being said, on a hot summer day this is pretty good at quenching thirst.
My favorite of the mexican beers.  Nice dark color.  A little watered down for this style, but that is part of its appeal when mixed with Mexican cuisine.
Really good with Mexican food.  Light and really carbonated.  Dont think Id like to drink this by itself, but it is a nice compliment to the food.
Yuck.  I had to try it being a turbo dog fan, but pretty unimpressive attempt by Abita here.  A little too fruity for me.  Aftertaste led me to get through this one in as few drinks as possible.

Golden in color, obviously.  Mine had a head that left about a quarter of the bottle laying on the bar in front of me.  I would attribute most of this to the subzero glass it was served in.  After tasting I didnt mind that I lost part of it.  My worst experience for a CBC brew.

Amber color with pleasant apricot scent.  Im generally not into the fruit flavored beers, but I do occasionally like this one.  The apricot is not overpowering and you get a nice taste of hops as well.  One of the few fruity beers I can have more than one of.
Comforting roasty nutty malted flavor.  I really enjoy the slightly bitter cocoa finish.
